@NODE Configuring "How to configure FreeMouse...."

FreeMouse is configured entirely through ToolTypes:

CX_POPKEY  -  the hotkey combination to bring up the GUI.  Default: ctrl-alt-f

CX_POPUP  -  set to YES if you want the GUI to appear when FreeMouse loads.

Speed  -  set to the desired mouse speed, in percent.

ClickToFront  -  set to YES if you want the ClickToFront mode switched on.

MMBShift  -  set to YES if you want the middle mouse button hack switched on.

The Speed, ClickToFront, and MMBShift settings can be changed at runtime via
a simple GadTools GUI which can be shown by pressing the HotKey combination.
You will have to change the tooltypes to change the settings permanently.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Features "Features...."

So what does FreeMouse actually do?

»   It provides fractional scaling of mouse movements.  The mouse speed can
    be adjusted continuously from 38% to 300%.

»   It provides my personally favoured Click-To-Front behaviour.  Double-click
    anywhere within the border of a window and it will jump to the front.

»   It provides the stereotypical middle mouse button shift function, with a
    slight twist - a click of the middle mouse button will mapped to a left-click
    with the shift key held down, so icons can be multi-selected with the middle
    button.

The latter two functions were included simply to reduce the number of hacks in
my WBStartup Drawer, and can be turned off easily.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Credits "Credits...."

FreeMouse was written during 1998 and 1999 by Alastair M. Robinson, mainly
for fun and to brush up on my C skills.

It was compiled with VBCC 0.6a, which is totally brilliant.  The provided
build script should work as long as both VBCC and the Native Developers Kit
includes (which can be obtained on the Amiga Developers CD) are installed.

